<h2 id="heading-0">The Accounting Method That Costs You $10K</h2>

<p>Most Texas business owners use the wrong accounting method. They're either:</p>

<ul>
<li>Stuck in cash basis when accrual would save them money</li>
<li>Using accrual when cash basis would reduce their taxes</li>
<li>Unsure which to use (this is most people)</li>
</ul>

<p>The difference isn't just "how you record stuff." It's real money - thousands of dollars in tax savings or extra payments every year.</p>

<p>Let me show you exactly how to choose and when to switch.</p>

<h2 id="heading-1">Cash Basis Accounting: Simple But Powerful</h2>

<h3 id="heading-2">How It Works</h3>

<p>You record revenue when you receive payment. You record expenses when you pay them.</p>

<p><strong>Example:</strong> You send an invoice in December but get paid in January. Under cash basis, you don't record the revenue until January.</p>

<h3 id="heading-3">Who Can Use Cash Basis</h3>

<ul>
<li><strong>Small businesses:</strong> Under $25 million average revenue</li>
<li><strong>Simple operations:</strong> Few inventory items</li>
<li><strong>Service businesses:</strong> Consulting, professional services</li>
<li><strong>Most Texas small businesses</strong></li>
</ul>

<h3 id="heading-4">Tax Advantages in Texas</h3>

<ul>
<li><strong>Defer income:</strong> Delay recognizing revenue to lower tax brackets</li>
<li><strong>Accelerate deductions:</strong> Pay expenses early to reduce current taxes</li>
<li><strong>Tax planning:</strong> Time income and expenses for optimal tax outcomes</li>
<li><strong>Cash flow control:</strong> Better matching of tax payments to cash availability</li>
</ul>

<h2 id="heading-2">Accrual Basis Accounting: Complex But Precise</h2>

<h3 id="heading-3">How It Works</h3>

<p>You record revenue when you earn it (send invoice). You record expenses when you incur them (receive bill).</p>

<p><strong>Example:</strong> You send an invoice in December. Under accrual, you record the revenue in December, even if payment comes in January.</p>

<h3 id="heading-4">Who Must Use Accrual</h3>

<ul>
<li><strong>Large businesses:</strong> Over $25 million average revenue</li>
<li><strong>Public companies:</strong> Required by law</li>
<li><strong>Inventory businesses:</strong> Required for accurate cost tracking</li>
<li><strong>C-Corporations:</strong> Generally required</li>
</ul>

<h3 id="heading-5">Tax Advantages</h3>

<ul>
<li><strong>Smooth income:</strong> Avoid tax bracket jumps from lumpy revenue</li>
<li><strong>Accurate matching:</strong> Expenses match revenue periods</li>
<li><strong>Inventory tracking:</strong> Proper cost of goods sold calculation</li>
<li><strong>Loan qualification:</strong> More accurate financial statements</li>
</ul>

